SIMPLE: incense
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incense
<hw>In*cense"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Incensed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Incensing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>incensus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>incendere</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets>
in + root of <ets>candere</ets> to glow. See <er>Candle</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To set on fire; to inflame; to kindle; to
burn.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Twelve Trojan princes wait on thee, and labor to
<qex>incense</qex>⟦br⟧
Thy glorious heap of funeral.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inflame with anger; to enrage; to enkindle; to
fire; to incite; to provoke; to heat; to madden.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people are <qex>incensed</qex> him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To enrage; exasperate; provoke; anger; irritate;
heat; fire; instigate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incense</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Incense
<hw>In"cense</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Incensed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Incensing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LL.
<ets>incensare</ets>: cf. F. <ets>encenser</ets>. See <er>Incense</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To offer incense to. See <er>Incense</er>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perfume with, or as with, incense.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Incensed</xex> with wanton sweets.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Marston.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incense</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Incense
<hw>In"cense</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>encens</ets>, F. <ets>encens</ets>, L. <ets>incensum</ets>, fr.
<ets>incensus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>incendere</ets> to burn. See
<er>Incense</er> to inflame.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The perfume or odors exhaled from spices and gums
when burned in celebrating religious rites or as an offering to some
deity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A thick cloud of <qex>incense</qex> went up.</q> <rj><qau>Ezek.
viii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The materials used for the purpose of producing a
perfume when burned, as fragrant gums, spices, frankincense,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nadab and Abihu, the sons of Aaron, took either of them his
censer, and put fire therein, and put <qex>incense</qex> thereon.</q>
<rj><qau>Lev. x. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Also used figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or heap the shrine of luxury and pride,⟦br⟧
With <qex>incense</qex> kindled at the Muse's flame.</q>
<rj><au>Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Incense tree</b></col>, <cd>the name of several balsamic
trees of the genus <gen>Bursera</gen> (or <gen>Icica</gen>) mostly
tropical American. The gum resin is used for incense. In Jamaica the
<spn>Chrysobalanus Icaco</spn>, a tree related to the plums, is called
<ex>incense tree</ex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Incense wood</b></col>, <cd>the
fragrant wood of the tropical American tree <spn>Bursera
heptaphylla</spn>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incense-breathing</ent>⟦br⟧
